The '''deific decree delusion''' is a [[defense (legal)|defense]] in a [[criminal case]] in which a person committed a crime in the belief that God ordered them to do it.<ref name=CL>''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora Binder]], {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}, [https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/]</ref>{{rp|615–626}} It is an example of a [[command hallucination]].<ref name=CL/>{{rp|615–626}} The [[perpetrator]] is [[legally insane]] because they are [[incapable of distinguishing right from wrong]].<ref name=CL/>{{rp|615–626}}

