{{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Marc Crépon | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Marc Crepon 20100329 Salon du livre de Paris 1.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Marc Crépon at Paris Book Fair in March 2010 | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|03|30|df=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Academic and philosopher | language = | nationality = French | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = Ecole Normale Superieure | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = Leadership | movement = | notableworks = <!-- or: | notablework = --> | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = Winner of the Bronze medal at the CNRS (2001) | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }}
'''Marc Crépon ''' (born 30 March 1962) is a French philosopher and academic who writes on the subject of languages and communities in the French and German philosophies and contemporary political and moral philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens.fr/recherche/portraits/article/marc-crepon?lang=fr|title=Marc Crépon - École normale supérieure - Paris|work=ens.fr}}</ref> He has also translated works by philosophers such as [[Nietzsche]], [[Franz Rosenzweig]] and Leibniz.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}
He is chair of Philosophy at the [[Ecole Normale Superieure]] and director of research at the Archives Husserl, National Center for Scientific Research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/whats_onpritzker-military-presentsmarc-crepon-and-michael-naas-trial-hate/|title=Commemorating World War One: The Trial of Hate, A conversation with French Author Marc Crépon and Translator Michael Naas. - Pritzker Military Museum & Library - Chicago|work=pritzkermilitary.org}}</ref>
== Early life == He was born in Decize, Nievre in 1962. After high school, Crépon completed a preparatory course at [[Lycee Condorcet]] in [[Paris]].<ref name="frenchculture.org">{{cite web|url=http://frenchculture.org/books/events/trial-hatred-marc-crepon|title=THE TRIAL OF HATRED - MARC CREPON|work=frenchculture.org}}</ref> He then attended the [[Ecole Normale Superieure]] and passed the [[agrégation]] in 1986, a French civil service exam for positions in public education.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}
The topic of his dissertation (written in French) was ''The problem of human diversity: survey on the characterization of the people and the constitution of geographies of spirit from Leibniz to Hegel'' (1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/probleme-de-la-diversite-humaine-enquete-sur-la-caracterisation-des-peuples-et-la-constitution-des-geographies-de-lesprit-de-leibniz-a-hegel/oclc/490132426/editions?editionsView=true&referer=br|title=Formats and Editions of Le problème de la diversité humaine : enquête sur la caractérisation des peuples et la constitution des géographies de l'esprit de Leibniz a Hegel [WorldCat.org]|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>
== Career == Crépon's first academic position was teaching philosophy at [[Nanterre University]]. Shortly after this, he moved to [[Moldova]] for a period and credits living and working in the USSR with developing many of his attitudes and pedagogical methods.<ref name="frenchculture.org"/> At this time, he also developed an interest in the relationship between political and linguistic communities, which he would go on to research in greater detail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens.fr/recherche/portraits/article/marc-crepon|title=Marc Crépon - École normale supérieure - Paris|work=ens.fr}}</ref>
He has traveled and lectured at American universities, including [[University of California, Irvine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanities.uci.edu/SOH/calendar/events.php?recid=4298&dept_code_val=all&event_cat=archive&file_name=events_arch|title=The Trial of Hatred" - Marc Crépon|work=uci.edu}}</ref> and [[Rice University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frenchculture.org/books/events/marc-crepon-houston|title=Marc Crépon in Houston|work=frenchculture.org}}</ref> Crépon also taught classes while in residence at [[Northwestern University]] in Chicago in 2006 and in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buffett.northwestern.edu/documents/newsletters/Newsletter2006Fall.pdf |format=PDF |title=CICS Newsletter |date=2006 |publisher=Buffett.northwestern.edu|accessdate=2015-08-01}}</ref>
Marc Crépon was the co-founder (along with [[Bernard Stiegler]]) of the association ''Ars Industrialis''.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}
== Publications ==
Marc Crépon has written 16 books in French,{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} the most notable of which are listed below.
* ''Le malin genie des langues : Nietzsche, Heidegger, Rosenzweig''. Title trans: The Evil Genius of Language: Nietzsche, Heidegger, Rosenzweig. Paris : Vrin, 2000. {{ISBN|2711614344}}. OCLC 876603414. * ''Les promesses du langage : Benjamin, Rosenzweig, Heidegger''. Title trans: The promises of language: Benjamin, Rosenzweig, Heidegger. Paris : J. Vrin, 2001. {{ISBN|2711615200}}. OCLC 876603462. * ''De la democratie participative : fondements et limites'' (with [[Bernard Stiegler]]). Title trans: Participatory Democracy: Foundations and limits. [Paris] : Mille et une nuits, [2007]. {{ISBN|9782755500332}}. OCLC 876604004. * ''Derrida, la tradition de la philosophie'' (with Frédéric Worms). Title trans: Derrida, the tradition of the philosophy. Paris : Galilée, impr. 2008. {{ISBN|9782718607627}}. OCLC 494480595. * ''The thought of death and the memory of war'' (with Michael Maurice Loriaux). Minneapolis, MN : University of Minnesota Press, 2013. {{ISBN|9780816680054}}. OCLC 840465545. * ''The death penalty''. Chicago ; London : University of Chicago Press, 2014-. {{ISBN|9780226144320}}. OCLC 865494962.
